{{History of the Byzantine Empire}}
A '''''katepanikion''''' ({{lang-el|κατεπανίκιον}}) was a [[Byzantine]] term for an area under the control of a ''[[katepano]]''. It was used to describe two different types of administrative divisions:
* From ca. 971 until the late 11th century, it referred to large circumscriptions comprising several [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]]s and commanded by a ''[[dux|doux]]'' ("duke") or ''[[katepano]]'' ("catepan"). In English, the divisions are usually termed "duchy" (in Greek ''doukaton'') or "catepanate" (''katepanikion''). * In the [[Palaiologan period]], the ''katepanikion'' became a much smaller province comprising a fortified town and its surroundings or an island, under a ''[[kephale (Byzantine Empire)|kephale]]'' and also termed a ''kephalatikion''.
==See also== *[[Catepanate of Italy]] *[[Catepanate of Ras]]
