== See also == *{{C|French Cameroons|French Cameroons topics}} **[[List of colonial governors of French Cameroons]] *[[Colonial heads of British Cameroon|Colonial governors of British Cameroon (Cameroons)]] *[[Heads of government of British Cameroon|Heads of government of British Cameroon (Cameroons)]] *[[Colonial heads of German Cameroon|Colonial heads of German Cameroon (Kamerun)]] *[[Colonial heads of Ambas Bay|Colonial heads of Ambas Bay (Victoria Colony)]]
[[Category:French colonial people in Cameroun|Heads of government]] [[Category:Government of Cameroon]] [[Category:Lists of French colonial governors and administrators|Cameroons]] [[Category:Lists of heads of government|French Cameroon]] [[Category:Cameroon-related lists|French heads of government]]

This is a list of the largest river basins without fragmentation by [[dam]]s in their catchments, ordered by average annual discharge.

To qualify for inclusion, a river must not only have no dams on its “main” stem, but also no dams on any tributary. For this reason, major world rivers such as the [[Amazon River|Amazon]], [[Lena River|Lena]], [[Irrawaddy River|Irrawaddy]], [[Amur River|Amur]], and [[Fraser River|Fraser]] are disqualified because of dams on tributary streams.

Many of the rivers in this list have uncertain discharges. With the exception of those in Russia, streamgauges have seldom (if ever) been placed on the majority of the largest unfragmented river systems, due to the remoteness and/or ruggedness of the terrain in which they are located. Apart from the Fly which is clearly the largest, all ranks listed here are not perfectly certain, and there also exist a number of rivers in [[Sundaland]] that might qualify with reliable discharge data, such as the [[Kapuas River|Kapuas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pdf.wri.org/watersheds_2003/as14.pdf|title=Watersheds of Asia and Oceania: AS 13 Kapuas|publisher=}}</ref>

