'''Otto Hilgard Tittmann''' (August 20, 1850 – August 21<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/138400793/?terms=Otto%2BHilgard%2BTittmann|title=Dr. Otto Tittmann Dies in Virginia|last=|first=|date=1938|work=St. Louis Post Dispatch|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref>, 1938) was a [[German-American]] [[geodesist]], [[geographer]], and [[astronomer]]

==Biography==
Tittmann was born in 1850, in [[Belleville, Illinois]]<ref name="noaa.gov">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.noaa.gov/cgsbios/biot5.html|title=NOAA History - Profiles in Time/C&GS Biographies - Dr. Otto Hilgard Tittmann|website=www.history.noaa.gov}}</ref> to [[revolutionary]] parents fleeing the aftermath of the [[1848 revolutions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.org/2012/11/30/a-gallant-gentleman-an-ideal-friend/|title=A Gallant Gentleman, an Ideal Friend|first1=Cathy|last1=Hunter|first2=Cathy|last2=Hunter|date=30 November 2012|website=National Geographic Society (blogs)}}</ref> He attended school in [[St. Louis]], and in 1867 joined the [[U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey]].<ref name="noaa.gov"/> In 1874 he was assistant astronomer in [[Japan]] to view the transit of [[Venus]], and from 1889 until 1893 he was in charge of weights and measures. In 1888 he co-founded the [[National Geographic Society]], and from 1895 until 1900 he was assistant in charge of the US Coast and Geodetic Survey. From 1900 until 1915 he was Superintendent of the Survey, and from 1915 until 1919 he was president of the National Geographic Society. He died in [[Leesburg, Virginia]], in 1938.

